Preface

This is the code of a mid-semester assignment for the TU Berlin Module Data Science for agent-based transport simulations WiSe 20/21. The aim was to look into the GTFS Data of the VBB Berlin transport association.

Preparation

Trying to get some interesting data on the service density, we want to count the passings of each stop. By that we get the information about how often a stop location is serviced. The analysis was reduced to the agencies BVG and S-Bahn Berlin. The modes were limited to bus (BVG), tram (~light train) (BVG), U-Bahn (~metro) (BVG) and S-Bahn (DB). Since the most services are symmetrical, we dont want to count the stop passings of one stop location for two directions. One direction should be deleted from the data set. Trying not to remove a non symmetrical service, like the Ring-Bahn, we identified all non symmetrical services, whose data points wont be touched. This proufed to be unneccesary since non symmetrical service only have a direction_id 0. So, deleting by direction_id 1 would have been enough.

# identify non symmetrical services
one_directer <- routes %>% 
  left_join(trips) %>% 
  select(route_id, route_short_name, agency_id, route_type, trip_headsign, direction_id) %>% 
  group_by(route_short_name) %>% 
  summarise(uni_dir = (unique(direction_id))) %>% 
  count(route_short_name) %>% 
  filter(n < 2) %>% 
  select(route_short_name)
## Joining, by = "route_id"
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'route_short_name' (override with `.groups` argument)
one_directer <- one_directer[["route_short_name"]]

head(one_directer)
## [1] "114" "175" "234" "271" "275" "312"
# Filter for BVG and S-Bahn Berlin
agency_filter = "[Bb]erlin"

# Get coordinates for each stop
berlin = agency %>% 
  select(agency_id, agency_name) %>% 
  filter(str_detect(agency_name, agency_filter)) %>% 
  inner_join(select(routes, route_short_name, agency_id, route_id, route_type)) %>% 
  inner_join(select(trips, route_id, trip_id)) %>% 
  inner_join(select(stoptime, trip_id, stop_id)) %>% 
  select(-trip_id) %>% unique() %>% 
  inner_join(select(stops, stop_id, stop_name, lat=stop_lat, lon=stop_lon)) %>% 
  unique()
## Joining, by = "agency_id"
## Joining, by = "route_id"
## Joining, by = "trip_id"
## Joining, by = "stop_id"
# building a selective stops count tibble including the counts of trips passings
berlin_cnt = agency %>% 
  select(agency_id, agency_name) %>% 
  filter(str_detect(agency_name, agency_filter)) %>% 
  inner_join(select(routes, route_short_name, agency_id, route_id, route_type)) %>% 
  inner_join(select(trips, route_id, trip_id, direction_id)) %>% 
  # filter out one direction for symmetrical service
  filter(route_short_name %in% one_directer | !(route_short_name %in% one_directer) & direction_id == 0) %>% 
  inner_join(select(stoptime, trip_id, stop_id)) %>% 
  group_by(agency_id, stop_id, route_type) %>% summarise(cnt = n()) %>% 
  inner_join(select(stops, stop_id, stop_name, lat = stop_lat, lon = stop_lon)) %>% 
  unique()
## Joining, by = "agency_id"
## Joining, by = "route_id"
## Joining, by = "trip_id"

# colour definition (modes)
berlin_modes = data.frame(route_type = c(700, 109, 400, 900),
                          mot = factor(x = c("Bus", "SBahn", "UBahn", "Tram"),
                                       levels = c("Bus", "SBahn", "UBahn", "Tram")

                          )
factpal = colorFactor(palette = c("#9b266d", "#368334", "#4990bc", "#c50800"),
                      domain = berlin_modes$mot,

Finishing the final tibble icluding all data for the plot of stop passings by districts. In our case (mot = NA) means ferries and (bezirk = NA) hints at a data point outside berlin. The steps of data wrangling include: * getting the districts name of the stop * getting the sum of all stops passings per district * removing outer berlin and ferries * pivoting into wider form for modes * replacing NAs with zeros * join with the district shapes * setting as sf object (attribute keeps getting lost by joining (needed for plot))

berlin_cnt_super <- berlin_cnt %>% 
  mutate(
    bezirk = shape_super[as.numeric(st_within(point, shape_super)),]$NAME
    ) %>% 
  group_by(bezirk, mot) %>% 
  summarise(n = sum(cnt)) %>% 
  filter(
    !(is.na(bezirk)) & !(is.na(mot))
    ) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = mot, values_from = n) %>% 
  mutate_all(
    ~replace(., is.na(.), 0)
    )%>% 
  rename(NAME = bezirk,
         BUS = Bus,
         SBAHN = SBahn,
         UBAHN = UBahn,
         TRAM = Tram
         ) %>% 
  mutate(
    ALL_MODES = sum(BUS, TRAM, SBAHN, UBAHN)
    ) %>% 
  left_join(shape_super) %>% 
  select(NAME, POPULATION, AREA,
         BUS, TRAM, UBAHN,
         SBAHN, ALL_MODES, geometry
         ) %>% 
  st_sf()

It would be nice to have the number of stops per mode, but one can see a lot of stops per route unused by main line service, used by detour trips (maybe caused by construction work). More work is necessary.

Only rough conclusions concerning the spatial distribution of service are possible. They might really be misleading and if not, should be made by mode with the network in mind.

Barplot

This barplot shows the stop passings by districs.

plot_bar_cnt <- berlin_cnt_super %>% 
  st_drop_geometry() %>% 
  pivot_longer(c(BUS, TRAM, UBAHN, SBAHN), names_to = "MODE", values_to = "N") %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = NAME, y = N, fill = MODE),
           stat = "identity",
           position = "dodge") +
  coord_flip() +
  guides(x = guide_axis(angle = 0)) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c("#9b266d", "#368334", "#c50800", "#4990bc")
    ) +
  theme() +
  labs(title = "Number of passing trips",
       subtitle = "per district",
       x = "",
       y = "",
       fill = "Mode"
       )

Service density plot by Planungsraum

The mapping by district is very coarse. We swith to plotting by mode and by the more detailed Planungsrume. Here the code for one mode.

# reread data after wrangling
setwd_data()
shape_districts_parts <- read_sf(dsn = "LOR_SHP_2019-1", layer = "Planungsraum_EPSG_25833")
setwd_work()

shape_districts_parts <- shape_districts_parts %>% 
  group_by(SCHLUESSEL) %>% 
  summarise() %>% 
  filter(!is.na(SCHLUESSEL)) %>% 
  #rename(NAME = BEZIRKSREG) %>% 
  mutate(AREA = st_area(geometry)) %>% 
  select(SCHLUESSEL, AREA, everything()) %>% 
  st_sf()
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
st_crs(shape_districts_parts) <- 25833

# pepare data for different plots
pre_plot_part <- berlin_cnt %>% 
  mutate(
    SCHLUESSEL = shape_districts_parts[as.numeric(st_within(point, shape_districts_parts)),]$SCHLUESSEL
  ) %>% 
  group_by(SCHLUESSEL, mot) %>% 
  summarise(n = sum(cnt)) %>% 
  filter(
    !(is.na(SCHLUESSEL)) & !(is.na(mot))
  ) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = mot, values_from = n) %>% 
  mutate_all(
    ~replace(., is.na(.), 0)
  ) %>% 
  rename(BUS = Bus,
         SBAHN = SBahn,
         UBAHN = UBahn,
         TRAM = Tram
  ) %>% 
  mutate(
    ALL_MODES = sum(BUS, TRAM, SBAHN, UBAHN)
  ) %>% 
  left_join(shape_districts_parts) %>% 
  select(SCHLUESSEL, AREA, BUS,
         TRAM, UBAHN, SBAHN,
         ALL_MODES, geometry
  ) %>% 
  st_sf()
